CTF Writeup: GDB Baby Step 2
picoCTF | Reverse Engineering Challenge


-----------------------------------------------------------
WHAT WAS THIS CHALLENGE?
-----------------------------------------------------------

One binary file was provided: debugger0_b. The goal was to figure out what value
is stored in the eax register at the end of the main function and submit it as
a decimal number in the picoCTF flag format. No source code was given. GDB was
used to read and understand the compiled assembly.


-----------------------------------------------------------
STEP 1 - Download the Binary
-----------------------------------------------------------

Command used:
wget https://artifacts.picoctf.net/c/520/debugger0_b

What happened:
The binary was downloaded into the current directory. Running ls confirmed it was
present. Running cat debugger0_b printed unreadable gibberish because it is a
compiled binary and not a text file. This confirmed that a proper debugger was
needed to analyze it.

Remember: cat works for text files. For binaries you need tools like GDB, objdump,
or Ghidra to make sense of the contents.


-----------------------------------------------------------
STEP 2 - Open the Binary in GDB
-----------------------------------------------------------

Command used:
gdb debugger0_b

What happened:
GDB loaded the binary and showed that no debugging symbols were found. This is
normal for compiled binaries without debug info. It just means function and
variable names will not be shown automatically, but we can still disassemble.

Running info functions inside GDB listed all known functions and confirmed that
main exists at address 0x0000000000401106.

Remember: info functions is a good first command in GDB. It gives you a map of
where functions are so you know what to look at.


-----------------------------------------------------------
STEP 3 - Disassemble Main
-----------------------------------------------------------

Command used inside GDB:
disas main

What happened:
GDB printed the full assembly of the main function. The important lines were:

   movl   $0x1e0da, -0x4(%rbp)     stores first value into variable a
   movl   $0x25f,   -0xc(%rbp)     stores second value into variable b
   movl   $0x0,     -0x8(%rbp)     stores zero into variable i (loop counter)
   jmp    main+48                   jumps to loop condition first
   mov    -0x8(%rbp), %eax         loads i into eax
   add    %eax, -0x4(%rbp)         adds i to a
   addl   $0x1, -0x8(%rbp)         increments i by 1
   mov    -0x8(%rbp), %eax         loads i into eax again
   cmp    -0xc(%rbp), %eax         compares i with b
   jl     main+38                   jumps back if i is less than b
   mov    -0x4(%rbp), %eax         loads final value of a into eax
   ret                              returns, eax holds the answer

Remember: assembly reads from bottom to top for context but from top to bottom
for execution. The movl lines at the top always set up the starting values.


-----------------------------------------------------------
STEP 4 - Convert Hex Values to Decimal
-----------------------------------------------------------

Commands used inside GDB:
p/d 0x1e0da     =>   123098
p/d 0x25f       =>   607
p/d 0x0         =>   0

What happened:
The three hex values from the movl lines were converted to decimal. These are the
starting values of the three local variables used in the loop.

Remember: p/d in GDB prints a value in decimal. p/x prints in hex. Use these to
convert values quickly without doing the math manually.


-----------------------------------------------------------
STEP 5 - Reconstruct the Logic
-----------------------------------------------------------

Reading the assembly, the code maps to this equivalent C program:

    int a = 123098;
    int b = 607;
    int i = 0;

    while (i < b) {
        a = a + i;
        i = i + 1;
    }

    return a;

The loop runs 607 times, adding the current value of i to a each iteration.
This means the loop computes: a = 123098 + 0 + 1 + 2 + ... + 606

Remember: a while loop in assembly always follows the same pattern. A counter
variable, an increment line, a compare line, and a conditional jump back.


-----------------------------------------------------------
STEP 6 - Calculate the Result
-----------------------------------------------------------

Using the sum formula for consecutive integers from 0 to n:

    sum = n x (n + 1) / 2
        = 606 x 607 / 2
        = 183921

Adding the base value:

    123098 + 183921 = 307019

This is the final value stored in eax when main returns.

Remember: when you see a loop that adds an incrementing counter to a variable,
the sum formula n x (n+1) / 2 lets you calculate the result instantly without
simulating every iteration.


-----------------------------------------------------------
QUICK REFERENCE
-----------------------------------------------------------

wget URL                     Download the binary file
cat filename                 Confirm it is a binary (will print gibberish)
gdb filename                 Open the binary in GDB
info functions               List all known functions and their addresses
disas main                   Disassemble the main function
p/d 0xVALUE                  Convert hex to decimal inside GDB


